%S A394453 1,0,0,1,0,0,0,3,5,1,0,2,1,0,3,5,4,7,6,2,6,1,0,3,4,8,2,2,1,2,1,2,10,2,
%T A394453 5,4,3,4,7,4,3,6,5,6,7,2,1,10,16,7,0,10,9,7,3,9,8,3,2,4,3,0,16,5,3,2,
%U A394453 1,3,3,7,6,12,11,7,5,3,5,9,8,12,1,5,4,11,5,4,6,8,7,5,6,15
%N A394453 a(n) = number of iterations of f(n) = sigma(n) if sigma(n) < 2n (n deficient), else n / spf(n) (where spf(n) is the smallest prime factor), needed to reach a cycle, for n >= 2.
%C A394453 For n > 1, define f(n) as follows: if sigma(n) < 2n (n is deficient), then f(n) = sigma(n); otherwise (n is abundant or perfect), f(n) = n / p, where p is the smallest prime factor of n. Iterating f eventually enters a cycle. Up to 10^9, only two cycles have been observed: C0 of length 8 (3 -> 4 -> 7 -> 8 -> 15 -> 24 -> 12 -> 6 -> 3) and C1 of length 9 (52 -> 98 -> 171 -> 260 -> 130 -> 252 -> 126 -> 63 -> 104 -> 52). a(n) is the number of steps to first reach either cycle.
%C A394453 Empirical verification for all n up to 10^9 shows that the orbit always falls into one of these cycles; no other cycles have been found. Among all n <= 10^9, about 73.0429% enter C0 and 26.9571% enter C1 (based on a complete count).
%C A394453 Additional statistics based on the first 100000 numbers: the step count grows approximately like c log n, with c approximately 1.84 for C0 and c approximately 1.98 for C1; the step distribution for numbers entering C1 is bimodal (peaks at 11-13 and 17-21), while that for C0 is unimodal (peak at 17-20). Detailed data and analysis are available in the Lu 2026 preprint.
%H A394453 Lu Zhuofan, <a href="/A394453/b394453.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10001</a>
%H A394453 Zhuofan Lu, <a href="https://doi.org/10.6084/m9.figshare.31827448">Two Attractors in an Iteration System Based on the Sum of Proper Divisors and the Smallest Prime Factor</a>, figshare, preprint, 2026.
%e A394453 For n = 2: sigma(2) = 3, and 3 is in cycle C0, so a(2) = 1.
%e A394453 For n = 3, a(3) = 0 because 3 is in cycle C0.
%e A394453 For n = 9: 9 -> 13 -> 14 -> 24, and 24 is in cycle C0, so a(9) = 3.
%e A394453 For n = 16: 16 -> 31 -> 32 -> 63 -> 104, and 104 is in cycle C1, so a(16) = 3.
%Y A394453 Cf. A000203 (sigma), A005100 (deficient), A020639 (smallest prime factor).
%K A394453 nonn
